Recursion in Python means a function calling itself to solve smaller instances of the same problem, until you hit a base case.

Key points
- Base case ends the recursion.
- Python has a default recursion limit (about 1000). Deep recursion can cause RecursionError.
- Python does not optimize tail calls, so deep tail-recursive patterns can still blow the stack.
- Use recursion for tree/graph problems or clean divide-and-conquer on small depths; for large depths or performance-critical code, prefer iterative solutions or explicit stacks.

